  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "The evolution of anti-money laundering (AML) legislation has been a gradual process driven by increasing global awareness of financial crimes. Here's an overview of key developments:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- 1970 Bank Secrecy Act (US) - First significant legislation requiring financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Initial focus on drug-related financial crimes\n\n2. International Developments\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established\n- Created first international standards for combating money laundering\n- Developed comprehensive recommendations for national legal and regulatory systems\n\n3. Significant Expansion Post-9/11\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Expanded AML regulations\n- Increased reporting requirements\n- Enhanced international cooperation\n- Linked money laundering to terrorism financing\n\n4. Technological Adaptations\n- Regulations addressing digital currencies and cryptocurrency\n- Enhanced digital transaction monitoring\n- Stricter Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n- Implementation of advanced technological screening mechanisms\n\n5. Recent Trends\n- Increased global collaboration\n- More stringent penalties\n- Broader definitions of financial crimes\n- Enhanced transparency requirements\n- Focus on beneficial ownership disclosure\n\nThe legislative landscape continues to evolve in response to emerging financial technologies and sophisticated criminal techniques.",
